es%20were%20%26quot%3Bdisgusting.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BBodies%20are%20supposed%20to%20be%20treated%20with%20respect%20%E2%80%94%20you%20can't%20deal%20with%20people%20in%20that%20way%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.pastfactory.com%2Fculture%2Fweird-status-symbols-throughout-history%2F20%2F%5C%22%3Esaid%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cdiv%3E5.%20Crumbling%20structures%20were%20the%20hottest%20party%20spots%20in%20Victorian%20England.%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%224254%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Ruins%20of%20an%20old%20medieval%20castle%20-%20stock%20photo%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64e78bb752bc2d0019916bae%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%223190%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3ERuins%20of%20an%20old%20medieval%20castle%20-%20stock%20photo%3Cp%3EManuel%20Breva%20Colmeiro%2F%20Getty%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EIn%2018th-century%20Europe%2C%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.msn.com%2Fen-gb%2Ftravel%2Fnews%2Fbizarre-status-symbols-through-history%2Fss-AAXa8IV%23image%3D2%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Efollies%3C%2Fa%3E%20%E2%80%94%20or%20fake%20castle%20ruins%20%E2%80%94%20became%20all%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theatlantic.com%2Fscience%2Farchive%2F2018%2F04%2Ffake-ruins-europe-trend%2F558293%2F%5C%22%3Erage%3C%2Fa%3E%20among%20the%20aristocracy.%20The%20word%20is%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nytimes.com%2F2001%2F05%2F17%2Fliving%2Farchitectural-follies-of-no-use-but-delight.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ederived%20from%20the%20French%20word%20folie%2C%20meaning%20foolishness%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20few%20records%20of%20these%20structures%20exist.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERobert%20Rochfort%2C%20known%20as%20the%20%26quot%3Bwicked%20earl%2C%26quot%3B%20built%20a%20run-down%20structure%20in%20Westmeath%2C%20Ireland%2C%20deliberately%20made%20to%20resemble%20a